g.text: The TransformerEncoder is a stack of identical TransformerBlocks that process embedded input tokens sequentially. Each block refines the token representations using multi-head self-attention and
feed-forward layers, allowing the model to learn deep, context-aware relationships across the input sequence. The encoder preserves the input shape (B, T, ED) while enriching the information at
[K - Strike Price, T - Time to Maturity, S - Spot Price, - Implied Volatility]
Turns raw numerical input like [K, T, S, ] into a learnable embedding.
Optional way of doing the transformation:
- use_mlp = False: Simple linear projection Linear(input_dim, embed_dim)
- use_mlp = True: Two-layer MLP with ReLU in between

A module that runs multiple independent attention mechanisms ("heads") in parallel, each one focusing on different parts of the input. Each head has its own Query, Key, Value projections, they all use the same attention
function(e.g., ScaledDotProductAttention) and their outputs are concatenated and linearly projected.
- Each token becomes aware of the others in the same sequence (e.g., neighboring [K, T] grid points)
{Q=x @ W_Q ; K=x @ W_K ;V=x @ W_V} -> e.g.: Q = nn.Linear(ED, ED)
Each of these layers has its own weights and bias and is trained via backprop to extract the right attention patterns.
Split the full embedding into subspaces one per attention head.
Q = Q.view(B, T, numberOfheads(H), subspace_length(d_k)).transpose(1,2) -> ED=numberOfheads*subspace_length
- transpose need to move the head before the token dimension, because we want to group by the head first, then tokens.

2. Compute attention scores: scores = Q @ K.transpose(-2, -1) / sqrt(d_k)
